name: heptadecanal
Reason: Starting with the basic unit, n-alkanes typically have a linear relationship between carbon chain length and melting point due to increased van der Waals interactions. For instance, n-hexadecane (C16) has a melting point of around 18°C. Each additional CH2 group in a straight-chain alkane adds approximately 2°C to the melting point. Heptadecanal has one additional carbon than hexadecane, but it also has an aldehyde functional group at the end of the chain. Aldehydes generally have lower melting points than alkanes with a comparable carbon count due to the polarity of the carbonyl group disrupting the crystal lattice. However, in very long chain aldehydes such as heptadecanal, this effect is minimal due to the predominance of van der Waals interactions of the alkyl chain. Thus, we can estimate the aldehyde group slightly raises the melting point due to the ability of the carbonyl to participate in dipole-dipole interactions, but the effect is small, so we would add roughly 1°C for an aldehyde in a long-chain alkane.
Prediction: Approximately 19°C (18°C from the C16 alkane base + 2°C for the additional CH2 group - 1°C for the aldehyde group's effect)
